<div id="banner">
	<h1>• FLEEP •</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p><a href="../2002/fleep">Fleep</a> is an absolutely genius 42-part serial comic from <a href="http://www.shigabooks.com/">Jason Shiga</a>. Now I read some comics (mainly <a href="http://dir.salon.com/topics/tom_tomorrow/">This Modern World</a>, <a href="http://dir.salon.com/topics/ruben_bolling/">Tom the Dancing Bug</a>, and <a href="http://www.scottmccloud.com/comics/mi/mi.html">Morning Improv</a>) but this is the first time I&#8217;ve seen a <em>serial comic</em> that&#8217;s really worked.</p>

<p>Our Hero finds himself trapped a phone booth, surrounded concrete, with only what he has on him. Can he escape before oxygen runs out? Watch as he solves <em>daring math problems</em> and makes <em>brave phone calls</em> in an attempt to survive. <em>Genius!</em> (My only complaint is that the ending comes too quickly and is unfulfilling.)</p>

<p><a href="../2002/fleep">Read Fleep now.</a> (Shiga&#8217;s original presentation doesn&#8217;t really work in my browser, so I reformatted it as a normal web page.)</p>

<p><strong>Also:</strong> Our Hero, or someone very much like him, stars in Shiga&#8217;s previous strip: <a href="http://www.shigabooks.com/shigabooks/csfolder/busstop.html">Bus Stop</a></p>

<p class="posted">posted December 11, 2003 08:19 PM (<a class="category" href="http://www.aaronsw.com/weblog/cat_tv">TV</a>)  <a href="001090" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>

